05654nam a22009375i 9781501513756DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97815015137567 a10.1515/97815015137562doi  a(DE-B1597)545350  a(OCoLC)1158118266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP299.N4bD43 2020 7aLAN0090602bisacsh04a4152231 aDe Clercq, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Morphosyntax of Negative Markers :bA Nanosyntactic Account /cKaren De Clercq. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (X, 252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Generative Grammar [SGG] ,x0167-4331 ;v14400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgment -- tPart I: Aims and background -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Theoretical background: Nanosyntax -- tPart II: The internal structure of negative markers -- t3. Classification of negative markers -- t4. The crosslinguistic morphosyntax of negative markers -- t5. The internal syntax of a negative marker -- tPart III: Negative markers and their clausal syntax in English and French -- t6. The external syntax of negative markers in English -- t7. Diachronic change in French -- tPart IV: Remaining issues -- t8. Other syntactic perspectives on negation -- t9. Semantics -- t10. Conclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book applies the tools of nanosyntax to the natural language phenomenon of negation. Most work on negation is concerned with the study of sentence negation, while low scope negation or constituent negation is hardly ever systematically discussed in the literature. The present book aims to fill that gap, by investigating scopally different negative markers in a sample of 23 typologically diverse languages. A four-way classification of negative markers is argued for and it is shown how meaningful syncretism patterns arise across those four groups of negative markers in the language sample investigated. The syncretisms are meaningful in that they track the natural semantic scope of negation, and provide support to the idea that morphology is not arbitrary, but points to submorphemic structure. Consequently, this study leads to a decomposition of the negative morpheme into five privative features: Tense, Focus, Classification, Quantity and Negation proper. Finally, the book argues that sentence, constituent and lexical negation can all be treated in the same module of the grammar, i.e. syntax.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxNegatives. 4aAdjektive. 4aNanosyntax. 4aNegation. 4aTypologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Syntax.2bisacsh  aAdjectives.  aNanosyntax.  aNegation.  aTypology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Frontlist 2020z978311074316608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2020 Englishz978311070476108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2020z9783110704563oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97815015137700 cprintz978150152006840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150151375